metadata.name: The dice is cast #23
metadata.description:
When I started studying the code and learning the "random" functions in early July 2022, it made me think of randomness when throwing dice. It is random, but with these restrictions (3 six-sided dice = 216 possibilities). 

With this mindset and theme, I began to create this first attempt at generative art. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects, materials, etc. and play with them. For this series, I inserted blocks of polystyrene to give it substance. 

All the graphic elements, colours and random arrangements were created using P5.js. The photos of polystyrene and the dices are integrated.

Press ENTER to download as a jpg image. 

@Yomu Oyashi July 2022

The NFT licence 2.0

metadata.name: Echoes of Enough #151
metadata.description:
"Echoes of Enough" is a collection that explores self-worth, acceptance, and validation. The collection presents a visual representation of the struggles, doubts, and triumphs of recognizing our own value. Each piece delves into different aspects of ourselves and how they contribute to this feeling.

The seemingly chaotic yet orderly arrangement of the shapes in this collection reflects the tumultuous nature of the human experience. It speaks to the push and pull of self-doubt and the struggle to acknowledge one's own worth, while the raw and unrefined nature of the collection reflects the brutal reality of the human experience.

A hidden harmony beneath the surface represents the truth that we are all enough, just as we are. The collection invites the viewer to look within and acknowledge their own struggles and triumphs and to find comfort in the realization that the feeling of being enough is always present, like an echo that lingers. 

It is a reminder that we are enough, just as we are.



The artwork is fully created in javascript with the p5js library. 
The ideal viewing resolution is 1000x1000, and the artwork can be scaled to any size/resolution. The grain effect will fade slightly for higher resolutions.

metadata.name: Cave Etchings #102
metadata.description:
Cave Etchings are detailed line drawings generated from unedited AI images of caves, conjoining an AI process with a generative art process. The project is not just an exercise in aesthetics, it is about seeing things the way a computer 'sees'. The original AI cave series focused on how AI Computer Vision can imagine fantastical caves; in cave etchings, the software visualises pixel data as movement, rotating lines according to hue, saturation, and brightness values. The project is inspired by the artwork of Franklin Booth (1874- 1948).
More details here: https://www.plummerfernandez.com/works/cave-etchings/

Instructions:
‘s’ to save
‘h’ to save hi-res version (may look slightly different in viewport as the moiré effect can vary)
‘t’ to download a thank you message

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan
